Q1

Demographic information of the patients admitted into hospital is available in ADMISSION.csv. See https://mimic.physionet.org/mimictables/admissions/ for details of each field in this file. Summarize following variables using appropriate graphs:

  • admission year
  • admission month
  • admission week day
  • admission hour
  • length of hospital stay
  • admission type
  • number of admissions per patient
  • admission location
  • insurance
  • language
  • religion
  • martial status
  • ethnicity
  • death

Note it is possible that one patient (uniquely identified by the SUBJECT_ID) is admitted into hospital multiple times. When summarizing some demographic information, it makes sense to summarize based on only unique patients.

First try of parsing the data:

admission <- read_csv("/home/203bdata/mimic-iii/ADMISSIONS.csv",
                      col_types = cols(ROW_ID = col_integer(),
                                       SUBJECT_ID = col_integer(),
                                       HADM_ID = col_integer(),
                                       HOSPITAL_EXPIRE_FLAG = col_logical(),
                                       HAS_CHARTEVENTS_DATA = col_logical()))

Summarizing the Data

  • Admission year
admission %>% mutate(adm_year = year(ADMITTIME)) %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = adm_year)) + geom_bar(color = "white", fill = "lightblue3") + labs(title = "Barplot of Admission Year", x = "Year of Admission") + theme_minimal()

  • Admission month
admission %>% mutate(adm_month = month(ADMITTIME, label = T)) %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = adm_month)) + geom_bar(fill = "lightblue4" ) + labs(title = "Barplot of Admission Month", x = "Month of Admission") + theme_minimal()

  • Admission week day
admission %>% mutate(adm_day = day(ADMITTIME)) %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = adm_day)) + geom_bar(fill = "lightblue") + labs(title = "Barplot of Admission Day", x = "Day of the Month") + theme_minimal()

  • Admission hour
admission %>% mutate(adm_hour = hour(ADMITTIME)) %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = adm_hour)) + geom_bar(fill = "cadetblue") + labs(title = "Barplot of Admission Hour", x = "Hour of the Day") + theme_minimal()

  • Admission minute
admission %>% mutate(adm_min = minute(ADMITTIME)) %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = adm_min)) + geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 2) + labs(title = "Plot of Admission Minute", x = "Minute of Admission") + theme_minimal()

  • Length of hospital stay
admission %>% mutate(stay_length = as.numeric(as.duration(DISCHTIME-ADMITTIME)/ 86400)) %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = stay_length)) + geom_density() + labs(title = "Plot of Length of Hospital Stay", x = "Length of Stay (in days)") + theme_minimal()

  • Admission type
admission %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = ADMISSION_TYPE)) + geom_bar(fill = "lightblue3") + labs(title = "Barplot of Admission Type", x = "Admission Type") + theme_minimal()

  • Number of admissions per patient
admission %>% count(SUBJECT_ID) %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = n)) + geom_bar(fill = "lightblue4") + labs(title = "Frequency of Admissions per Patient", x = "Number of Admissions") + theme_minimal()

  • Admission location
admission %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = ADMISSION_LOCATION)) + geom_bar(fill = "lightblue") + coord_flip() + labs(title = "Barplot of Admission Location", x = "Admission Location") + theme_minimal()

  • Insurance
admission %>% distinct(SUBJECT_ID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = INSURANCE)) + geom_bar(fill = "cadetblue") + labs(title = "Plot of Patient Insurance", x = "Insurance") + theme_minimal()

  • Language
top_lang <- admission %>% distinct(SUBJECT_ID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>% count(LANGUAGE) %>% na.omit(LANGUAGE) %>% arrange(desc(n)) %>% slice(1:10)

#nb.cols <- 10

top_lang %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = LANGUAGE, y = n, fill = LANGUAGE)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + labs(title = "Top Seven Patient Languages", y = "count", x = "Language") + theme_minimal() + theme(legend.position = "none") #+ scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Blues")

  • Religion
admission %>% distinct(SUBJECT_ID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = RELIGION)) + geom_bar(fill = "lightblue3") + labs(title = "Plot of Patient Religion", x = "Religion") + theme_minimal() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

  • Marital status
admission %>% distinct(SUBJECT_ID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = MARITAL_STATUS)) + geom_bar(fill = "lightblue4") + labs(title = "Plot of Marital Status", x = "Marital Status") + theme_minimal() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

top_eth %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = ETHNICITY, y = n)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "lightblue") + labs(title = "Top Ten Patient Ethnicity", x = "Ethnicity", y = "count") + theme_minimal() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, size = 6))

Q2

Link the data in ADMISSION.csv and PATIENTS.csv (https://mimic.physionet.org/mimictables/patients/) and summarize following variables using appropriate graphs:

  • gender
  • age at admission

Solution

First let’s read and parse the PATIENTS.csv data.

patient <- read_csv("/home/203bdata/mimic-iii/PATIENTS.csv",
                    col_types = cols(ROW_ID = col_integer(),
                                     SUBJECT_ID = col_integer(),
                                     EXPIRE_FLAG = col_character()))

Let’s merge the ADMISSION.csv and PATIENTS.csv together by SUBJECT_ID

adm_unique <- admission %>% distinct(SUBJECT_ID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>% select("SUBJECT_ID","ADMITTIME")

patient_adm <- inner_join(patient, adm_unique, by = "SUBJECT_ID")
  • Gender
patient_adm %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = factor(GENDER), y = ..prop.., group = 1)) + geom_bar(stat = "count", fill = c("lightpink", "lightblue")) + scale_x_discrete(label = c("Female", "Male")) + labs(title = "Gender of Patients", y = "Proportion", x = "Gender") + theme_minimal()

  • Age at admission
patient_adm %>% mutate(age_adm = as.numeric(as.duration(ADMITTIME - DOB), "years")) %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = age_adm)) + geom_histogram(bins = 50, fill = "cadetblue") + labs(title = "Age of Patients", x = "Age (yrs)") + theme_minimal()

Let’s merge the ADMISSION.csv, PATIENTS.csv, ICUSTAYS.csv together by SUBJECT_ID

adm_unique <- admission %>% distinct(SUBJECT_ID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>% select("SUBJECT_ID","ADMITTIME")

Q4

CHARTEVENTS.csv (https://mimic.physionet.org/mimictables/chartevents/) contains all the charted data available for a patient. During their ICU stay, the primary repository of a patient’s information is their electronic chart. The ITEMID variable indicates a single measurement type in the database. The VALUE variable is the value measured for ITEMID.

D_ITEMS.csv (https://mimic.physionet.org/mimictables/d_items/) is the dictionary for the ITEMID in CHARTEVENTS.csv. Find potential values of ITEMID that correspond to systolic blood pressure, i.e., LABEL contains the string systolic.

Compile a tibble that contains the first ICU stay of unique patients, with the patient’s demographic information, the first systolic blood pressure measurement during ICU stay, and whether the patient died within 30 days of hospital admission.

Solution:

Let’s first read and parse the CHARTEVENTS.csv and D_ITEMS.csv data.

charts <- read_csv("/home/203bdata/mimic-iii/CHARTEVENTS.csv",
                   col_types = cols(ROW_ID = col_integer(),
                                     SUBJECT_ID = col_integer(),
                                     HADM_ID = col_integer(),
                                     ICUSTAY_ID = col_integer(),
                                     ITEMID = col_integer()))

ditems <- read_csv("/home/203bdata/mimic-iii/D_ITEMS.csv",
                   col_types = cols(ROW_ID = col_integer(),
                                    ITEMID = col_integer(),
                                    ABBREVIATION = col_character(),
                                    UNITNAME = col_character(),
                                    PARAM_TYPE = col_character(),
                                    CONCEPTID = col_integer()))
first_ICU <- icu %>% select("SUBJECT_ID" , "HADM_ID", "ICUSTAY_ID", "INTIME") %>% arrange(SUBJECT_ID, INTIME) %>% distinct(SUBJECT_ID, .keep_all = TRUE)

patient_demo <- patient %>% select("SUBJECT_ID","GENDER")

# first merge
tibble1 <- inner_join(first_ICU, patient_demo, by = "SUBJECT_ID")

admission_demo <- admission %>% select("SUBJECT_ID", "LANGUAGE", "RELIGION", "MARITAL_STATUS", "ETHNICITY") %>% distinct(SUBJECT_ID, .keep_all = TRUE) 

# second merge
tibble2 <- left_join(tibble1, admission_demo, by = "SUBJECT_ID")

systolic_ID <- ditems %>% filter(str_detect(LABEL, regex("systolic", ignore_case = TRUE))) %>% select("ITEMID", "LABEL")

charts_sys <- inner_join(charts, systolic_ID, by = "ITEMID")
first_sys <- charts_sys %>% select("SUBJECT_ID", "ICUSTAY_ID", "ITEMID", "CHARTTIME", "LABEL", "VALUE", "VALUEUOM") %>% arrange(SUBJECT_ID, CHARTTIME) %>% distinct(SUBJECT_ID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>% select("SUBJECT_ID", "LABEL", "VALUE", "VALUEUOM")

# third merge
tibble3 <- left_join(tibble2, first_sys, by = "SUBJECT_ID")

death_days <- as.numeric(as.duration(admission$DEATHTIME - admission$ADMITTIME), "days")

thirty_death <- admission %>% mutate(DDAYS = case_when(death_days >= 30 ~ "FALSE",
                                      death_days < 30 ~ "TRUE")) %>% arrange(SUBJECT_ID) %>% select("SUBJECT_ID", "DDAYS", "ADMITTIME", "DEATHTIME") %>% arrange(SUBJECT_ID, ADMITTIME) %>% distinct(SUBJECT_ID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>% select("SUBJECT_ID", "DDAYS")

# last merge
final_tibble <- inner_join(tibble3, thirty_death, by = "SUBJECT_ID")

final_tibble %>% print(width = Inf)
